<br>
My children area aware of the whole issue of gay and lesbian people as they are both scouts and were in scouts during the whole court/news thing regarding homosexual people in scouting. We also have some friends who are homosexual. While it is not our way of life, it is that of others. I teach my children tolerence and acceptance for people who have different lifestyles and belives then their own.  I allow them to play this game completely supervised and there are some servers where I do not allow them to play because there are alot more &quot;hunters of children&quot;  I very closely monitor my childrens game play and when I discover my childrens friends who play everquest I speak to their parents and inform them of the nature of the game and what types of issues their children are exposed to. I happen to be suprized that 99% of the parents of the children my kids are friends with let them play everquest with no clue what their children were actually doing.  <br>
<br>
I also happen to have many children who play with our guild or who are in our guild, and I always keep who the children are confidential to protect them from the &quot;children hunters&quot; I have many times had parents log on their childrens charicters and talk to me asking me questions regarding their kids and what they are doing online. I am happy to speak to parents and do so frequently.  <br>
<br>
When my children play everquest I sit beside them and watch their chat and what they are doing... <br>
<br>
The question is not do children play everquest, because we all know they do, its what are we as adults going to expose them to or are we ready to explain to them what they see and experience online?<br>
<br>
I know parents who let kids as young as 4 years old play the game, because they themselves play constantly and its a way to share their interests with thier kids. Do I agree with this, Im not sure. A 4 year old cannot yet read, and the game for them is pushing buttons to make &quot;monsters&quot; die.  a 10 year old playing the game can read, and is very impressionable. They will not understand much of the true experience of Everquest relationships and finess, but will be impacted by the game and have questions regarding the content and such... a 13 year old is developed much more and will understand more... ect... <br>
<br>
If Varrent didn't expect kids to play they would not have added language filters and GM's to help control the use of the game, they would not have added the user agreement that you must click ok to each time you play. <br>
<br>
**************<br>
ok whats my point?  I would like to here some stories from parents, I would like to know Do you allow your kids to play eq and how much do you monitor their play if you do... and are you really comfortable with answering questions regarding sexual orientation, sex and relationships and language with your children after their EQ experiences?<br>
*****************<br>
