<br>
My daughter played while I did (starting at 13), she still does on occasion, we had a lot of fun most of the time.  It was something we could do together.  She and I met some great people and walked away with some very close friends, some we were able to meet and still talk to all the time.  I read her logs to check up on her and some  didn't like, but nothing much went on there except the occasional pervert who I of course did not appreciate they way she was talked to.  BUT...I also have to look at it as a learning experience because it opened up a lot of conversations between us that may not of  happened without being exposed to certain situations.  <br>
<br>
I did not freak on bad language, because what I hear coming out of kids mouths around her school etc, is nothing different.  I wasn't thrilled with people who used it excessively but it wasn't as if it was shocking. I did not worry about racial jokes, gay jokes, etc because she was brought up to be a tolerant person and doesn't judge anyone by their race or sexual preferences.  She looks at people who feel the need to belittle others as the moron's that they are.<br>
<br>
Overall it was a good experience for both of us...until in the last  year it all seemed to change.  People used to be helpful to eachother and just enjoyed the fun of the game, the thrill of the hunt, having a good time together.  Then it seemed people just became too involved in the game and forgot it was a game.  People with nothing better to do than talk crap about one another, spread lies, or just attack innocent people for no reason.  She was cut out of a guild because I left (although she had nothing to do with the situation), called fat by people who had never even met her, and just plain put in uncomfortable situations that should never be a part of a game.   The game lost its innocent fun that made it great in the first place.  Luckily she is a great kid and didn't let these things bother her other than not enjoying the game anymore, which is the same that happend with myself.<br>
<br>
We both learned a hard lesson about people and the losers that can hide behind a character in a game because they don't have to answer to anyone.  We learned about how someone can pretend to be your friend but would stab you in the back over a game.  <br>
<br>
My son used to play at 4 and 5.  He couldn't really read so it wasn't a problem, now I won't let him play other than a newb char for a short amount of time with me hanging over his shoulder.<br>
<br>
Overall, I don't think either one of us would trade the stupidity of some bad times for the few wonderful lifetime friends we made along the way,  the times we shared, or the conversations we had over issues that may of not happened because the situations didn't arise, and most importantly the laughs with some very close friends.  <br>
<br>
Would I suggest it for any child now?  HELL NO!  I wouldn't suggest it for any adults either.  <br>
<br>
